== 3.2.1 Completeness Check

=== Objective

Verify that all key scenarios relevant to Team B's Missing Dependencies feature are covered by
at least one requirement. A requirement set is complete when no realistic user scenario falls
outside its scope.

=== Method

The team executed four concrete walkthroughs against the running Spring Boot application at
`http://localhost:8080/missing-dependencies`. Each walkthrough used a real modpack ZIP
containing known Fabric mods sourced from Modrinth, with dependency declarations taken directly
from their `fabric.mod.json` metadata files. Results were observed in the browser and in the
application console log.

=== Walkthrough W-C1: All Dependencies Present (Zero Missing)

*Setup:* A ZIP was uploaded containing `sodium-fabric-0.5.8+mc1.20.1.jar`,
`lithium-fabric-mc1.20.1-0.11.2.jar`, and `fabric-api-0.92.0+1.20.1.jar`. Sodium and Lithium
both declare `fabric-api` as a mandatory dependency. Fabric API was included in the upload.

*Steps executed:*

. The ZIP was uploaded via the upload interface.
. The backend parsed all three `fabric.mod.json` files.
. `DependencyResolverService.validate()` was called for each mod.
. `modRepository.findById("fabric-api")` returned a non-empty result for both checks.
. The `/missing-dependencies` page loaded.

*Observed result:* The `dependency-list` div rendered empty. The `empty-state` div
(`id="empty-state"`) became visible with the message "No missing dependencies were found."
No banners or download buttons appeared.

*Covering requirements:* DR-5 (Structural Validity), DR-10 (Resolution Result), Domain Event 9
(Modpack Configuration Validated), Domain Event 17 (Modpack Has Just Become Consistent).

*Validation outcome:* ✅ This scenario is fully covered. The system correctly identified a
valid configuration and displayed no false positives.

=== Walkthrough W-C2: All Dependencies Unresolved

*Setup:* A ZIP was uploaded containing a single fabricated mod file whose `fabric.mod.json`
declared three mandatory dependencies: `"unknown-lib-alpha"`, `"unknown-lib-beta"`, and
`"unknown-lib-gamma"`. None of these IDs exist on Modrinth. None were included in the upload.
The `DependencyCacheService` was cleared before the test using `invalidateAll()` called from a
temporary debug endpoint.

*Steps executed:*

. The ZIP was uploaded.
. `DependencyResolverService.validate()` identified all three as missing and mandatory.
. `DependencyApiClient.fetchVersionMetadata()` was called for each. Modrinth returned an
  empty JSON array `[]` for all three (IDs not found, distinct from an HTTP error).
. `DependencyParser.extractPreferredUrl()` returned `null` for all three.
. `DependencyParser.buildDto()` constructed fallback browse links:
  `https://modrinth.com/mod/unknown-lib-alpha`, etc.
. The `/missing-dependencies` page loaded.

*Observed result:* The `partial-results-banner` (`id="partial-results-banner"`) became visible.
All three dependencies appeared in the `dependency-list` with fallback browse links and
"Unresolved" badges. There was no distinct UI state indicating that *all* resolution attempts
failed — the partial-results banner was identical in appearance to the case where only some
dependencies failed.

*Covering requirements:* Section 2.3.3 notification requirement. Domain Event 14
(resolution failed branch).

*Validation outcome:* ⚠ Partially covered. The notification requirement covers the
individual-failure case but no requirement governs behavior when the failure is total. The
system displayed a partial-failure banner for a total-failure situation, giving the user no
indication that manual search is the only path forward for every listed dependency.

Finding C-1 — No requirement distinguishes total resolution failure from partial failure::
DR-10 lists "missing dependencies" as an output category but does not require the system to
differentiate between a partial and a total resolution failure. The `partial-results-banner`
element in `missing-dependencies.html` is the only failure-state UI element. During this
walkthrough it was rendered for a case where zero dependencies were resolved, which was
misleading.
+
*Requirement added:* +
DR-10a — Total Resolution Failure State: When dependency resolution completes and zero missing
dependencies were resolved (all resolution attempts returned a null URL and no cached entries
existed), the system shall display a total-failure message distinct from the partial-results
banner, explicitly informing the user that no automatic download links could be retrieved and
that all dependencies must be located manually.

=== Walkthrough W-C3: Modrinth API Unreachable

*Setup:* The Modrinth API base URL in `DependencyApiClient` was temporarily pointed to
`https://api.modrinth.invalid` to simulate DNS failure. A ZIP was uploaded containing
`iris-1.6.17+1.20.1.jar`, which declares a mandatory dependency on `sodium` (mod ID:
`"AANobbMI"`). Sodium was not included in the upload.

*Steps executed:*

. The ZIP was uploaded.
. `DependencyResolverService.validate()` identified `"AANobbMI"` (Sodium) as missing and
  mandatory.
. `DependencyApiClient.fetchVersionMetadata("AANobbMI", "fabric", "1.20.1")` threw an
  exception due to DNS resolution failure.
. The exception was caught; the method returned `null`.
. `DependencyParser.extractPreferredUrl(null, "AANobbMI")` returned `null`.
. `DependencyParser.buildDto()` constructed the fallback:
  `https://modrinth.com/mod/AANobbMI`.
. The page loaded showing one dependency entry with the fallback browse link.

*Observed result:* The dependency appeared in the list with a browse link and "Unresolved"
badge. The console logged: `[DependencyApiClient] HTTP error for mod 'AANobbMI': ...`. No
user-visible indication distinguished this fallback (caused by a network failure) from the
fallback in W-C2 (caused by a genuine absence on Modrinth).

*Covering requirements:* Section 2.3.3 retry requirement, Section 2.3.4 graceful degradation.

*Validation outcome:* ⚠ Partially covered. Graceful degradation was observed — the system
did not crash and did produce a usable fallback link. However, no retry mechanism exists in
`DependencyApiClient` and the fallback behavior (returning the browse link) is not stated as
a requirement anywhere in the document.

Finding C-2 — Fallback behavior after API failure is implemented but not required::
`DependencyParser.buildDto()` has silently implemented a fallback browse-link strategy.
This behavior was observed to function correctly during this walkthrough, but because it
is not stated in any requirement, it cannot be considered verified. Any future refactor
could remove it without violating any stated requirement.
+
*Requirement added:* +
DR-11 — API Fallback Presentation: When an API call to retrieve dependency metadata fails
(whether due to a network error, timeout, or HTTP error response), the system shall present
the user with a fallback browse link in the format `https://modrinth.com/mod/{encodedModId}`
and mark the dependency as unresolved. This fallback shall be visually distinct from a
successfully resolved direct download link.

=== Walkthrough W-C4: Circular Dependency Present

*Setup:* Two fabricated mod JARs were created. `mod-alpha`'s `fabric.mod.json` declared a
mandatory dependency on `mod-beta`. `mod-beta`'s `fabric.mod.json` declared a mandatory
dependency on `mod-alpha`. Both were included in the upload ZIP.

*Steps executed:*

. The ZIP was uploaded.
. `DependencyResolverService.validate()` was called for `mod-alpha`.
. `detectCircularDependency()` traversed: `mod-alpha` → `mod-beta` → `mod-alpha` (already in
  visited set).
. `mod-alpha` was added to the `circularDependencies` list.
. The `ValidationResponse` was returned with `circularDependencies = ["mod-alpha"]`.

*Observed result:* The circular dependency was detected and included in the response.
The `/missing-dependencies` page reflected the detection correctly.

*Covering requirements:* DR-9 (Circular Dependency Detection), Domain Event 6
(Circular Dependency Detected), Section 3.2 Scenario 2.

*Validation outcome:* ✅ Fully covered. The system correctly detected the cycle and reported
it without entering an infinite loop.

