== 3.2.2 Consistency Check

=== Objective

Verify that no two requirements in Team B's feature scope contradict each other. A requirement
set is consistent when satisfying one requirement does not make it impossible or ambiguous to
satisfy another.

=== Method

The team examined pairs of requirements governing related behavior and executed targeted
walkthroughs to observe whether both requirements could be satisfied simultaneously under
realistic conditions.

=== Walkthrough W-I1: Cache Behavior vs. Freshness on Re-Upload

*Setup:* A ZIP containing `iris-1.6.17+1.20.1.jar` (with Sodium as a missing mandatory
dependency) was uploaded. After the first upload, `DependencyCacheService` held an entry for
`"AANobbMI"` (Sodium) with a 30-minute TTL. The Modrinth API was then pointed to
`https://api.modrinth.invalid` to simulate unavailability. The same ZIP was immediately
re-uploaded.

*Observed result:* On re-upload, `DependencyCacheService.get("AANobbMI")` returned the
cached entry from the first upload. `DependencyApiClient` was never called. The page
displayed the same resolution result as the first upload, with no indication to the user
that cached data was being used.

Finding I-1 — Cache behavior and freshness on re-upload are underspecified::
Section 2.3.4 (Reliability) favors using cached data to handle API failures gracefully.
Section 2.3.3 (Interface Requirements) implies that Modrinth queries are performed to locate
mods — implying fresh data. No requirement states whether the cache should be invalidated
on re-upload. During this walkthrough the system silently served a cached result, which
was correct in this case but would be incorrect if a user re-uploaded after fixing a mod
ID typo in a previous attempt — the corrected ID would still resolve from the stale
cached entry for the original (wrong) ID.
+
*Requirement added:* +
DR-CACHE-1 — Cache Invalidation on Re-Upload: When a user submits a modpack for analysis,
the system shall invalidate any cache entries whose keys match the declared dependency
identifiers of the newly uploaded modpack before initiating resolution. This ensures that
re-analysis reflects current repository state rather than a result cached from a prior upload.

=== Walkthrough W-I2: Retry Behavior vs. Graceful Degradation Under Load

*Setup:* Ten concurrent upload requests were submitted using a test script, each containing
a different mod with one unresolvable dependency. The Modrinth API was live but throttled
(HTTP 429 responses) after the third request.

*Observed result:* `DependencyApiClient` has no retry mechanism — each request made exactly
one HTTP call and returned `null` on failure. Because there is no retry logic, the conflict
described below is currently latent rather than active.

Finding I-2 — Retry requirement and graceful degradation are in latent conflict::
Section 2.3.3 requires retries up to a configurable limit. Section 2.3.4 requires graceful
degradation under overload. If retries are implemented as specified, each failed request
could generate up to N additional outbound calls, multiplying API traffic under the exact
conditions (high load, throttling) where the graceful degradation requirement demands reduced
traffic. No requirement currently mediates between the two.
+
*Requirement revised:* +
Section 2.3.3 (revised): Failed API requests shall trigger automatic retries up to a
configurable limit, provided the system has not received an HTTP 429 (Too Many Requests)
response from the external API. When a 429 response is received, retries shall be suppressed
for the remainder of that resolution cycle and the browse-link fallback defined in DR-11
shall be used.

