== 3.2.3 Realism Check

=== Objective

Verify that no requirement in Team B's feature scope is technically unachievable or stated in
a way that cannot be confirmed through a concrete test. A requirement is realistic when it is
implementable within the project's constraints and testable against an observable pass/fail
outcome.

=== Method

Each requirement was evaluated against two criteria: (1) achievability within the project's
technical scope (Spring Boot, Modrinth API, no automated mod installation), and (2) testability
— whether a concrete test with a defined pass/fail criterion could be written for it.
Walkthroughs were executed to confirm whether the current implementation satisfied, violated,
or left untestable each requirement under review.

=== Walkthrough W-R1: Retry Limit Testability

*Setup:* An attempt was made to write a unit test for the retry behavior specified in
Section 2.3.3: "Failed API requests should trigger automatic retries up to a configurable
limit." A search was performed for `dependency.resolver.max-retries` or any equivalent
property in `application.properties` and `DependencyApiClient.java`.

*Observed result:* No retry mechanism exists in `DependencyApiClient`. No configurable
property exists for a retry limit. The requirement uses `should` rather than `shall`, making
it non-mandatory. No test could be written that would produce a pass/fail result for this
requirement as stated.

Finding R-1 — Retry limit requirement is untestable as written::
The requirement does not define where the limit is configured, what the default value is,
or whether the retries apply per-dependency or per-resolution-cycle. Without these specifics,
no test can confirm compliance.
+
*Requirement revised:* +
Section 2.3.3 (revised): Failed API requests shall trigger automatic retries. The maximum
retry count shall default to 3 and shall be configurable via the
`dependency.resolver.max-retries` key in `application.properties`. A JUnit test shall verify
that `DependencyApiClient` makes no more than `max-retries + 1` total attempts per dependency
per resolution cycle when the API returns an error response.

=== Walkthrough W-R2: Performance Requirement Testability

*Setup:* A timed integration test was written to measure how long `DependencyResolverService`
took to process a ZIP containing 20 Fabric mods, 7 of which had missing mandatory dependencies
requiring Modrinth API calls. The test was run three times on a local machine with a stable
network connection.

*Observed results:*

[cols="1,1"]
|===
|Run |Elapsed Time

|Run 1
|4.3 seconds

|Run 2
|4.8 seconds

|Run 3
|5.1 seconds

|===

*Finding:* The current Section 2.3.4 performance requirement states the system shall process
requests "efficiently, ensuring reasonable response times under typical user workloads." No
numeric threshold is defined. All three test runs would pass an undefined threshold but Run 3
would fail a 5-second threshold. The requirement cannot produce a definitive pass or fail
result as currently written.

Finding R-2 — Performance requirement uses undefined terms and cannot be tested::
The terms *efficiently*, *reasonable*, and *typical* carry no agreed numerical meaning within
the project. The test results above demonstrate that the system's performance is sensitive
to network latency on API calls, making a concrete threshold both necessary and achievable.
+
*Requirement revised:* +
Section 2.3.4 Performance (revised): The system shall return a complete dependency resolution
result within 6 seconds for a modpack containing up to 20 mods with up to 10 missing
mandatory dependencies, measured under a stable network connection with the Modrinth API
available. This threshold shall be verified by a timed integration test executed as part of
milestone testing. The 6-second threshold was derived from the three test runs recorded in
Section 3.2.3 Walkthrough W-R2 of this document, with a 1-second margin applied to the
observed maximum of 5.1 seconds.

=== Walkthrough W-R3: Absent Dependency vs. API Failure

*Setup:* Two separate uploads were performed. In the first, `iris-1.6.17+1.20.1.jar` was
uploaded without Sodium (`"AANobbMI"`), a real mod ID that exists on Modrinth. In the second,
a fabricated mod declaring `"nonexistent-mod-xyz-404"` as a mandatory dependency was uploaded.
This ID does not exist on Modrinth. The Modrinth API was available for both uploads.

*Observed results:* In both cases, `DependencyParser.extractPreferredUrl()` returned `null`
and `DependencyParser.buildDto()` produced a browse link. The `/missing-dependencies` page
displayed both with identical "Unresolved" badges. There was no visible distinction between
a dependency that exists on Modrinth but was not included in the upload versus one that
does not exist anywhere.

Finding R-3 — Domain Event 15 assumes all dependency IDs are locatable; no case for absent mods::
Domain Event 15 (Retrieved Mod Has Just Been Obtained) describes only the success path.
No domain event or requirement covers the case where a declared dependency ID returns an
empty result array from Modrinth (HTTP 200, `[]`) — meaning the mod does not exist in the
repository at all, as distinct from a network failure. The current implementation handles
this silently via the `null` return path, but this behavior is not required anywhere and
the user receives no information distinguishing a missing-but-findable mod from a
missing-and-unfindable one.
+
*Requirement added:* +
DR-12 — Unresolvable Dependency Handling: When the Modrinth API returns an empty result set
(HTTP 200 with an empty array) for a given dependency identifier, the system shall classify
that dependency as `unresolvable` — distinct from `unresolved` (which indicates an API
communication failure). The Missing Dependencies page shall display `unresolvable` dependencies
with a label indicating the mod could not be found in the repository, as opposed to a label
indicating a network or retrieval error.

